# Git commits (granularity and messages)

## When to commit

**Commit after each small logical unit of work**, not only at the end of a large task. Examples:

- After adding **one** feature component or user-visible slice
- After **fixing one** bug (one cause / one fix)
- After **refactoring one** specific area (not a whole-repo sweep in one commit)
- After **writing tests** for **one** behaviour or module

If a session touches several unrelated concerns, use **several commits** so history stays readable and reverts stay safe.

## Commit messages

- **Short** — one line subject (roughly ≤ 72 characters is a good habit)
- **Specific** — says *what* changed, not “stuff” or “updates”
- **Action-oriented** — imperative mood, like a concise instruction (common convention: “Add…”, “Fix…”, “Refactor…”, “Update…”)

### Good examples

- `Add pagination to orders endpoint`
- `Fix null check in payment webhook`
- `Refactor file upload handler`
- `Update README setup instructions`

### Weak examples (avoid)

- `stuff`, `changes`, `fixes`, `work on project`, `wip`, `updates`

### Project examples (same bar as `docs/DEVELOPMENT.md`)

| Prefer | Avoid |
|--------|--------|
| `Add set-length option to performance form` | `changes`, `fixes`, `wip` |
| `Fix bulk add range when event dates shown` | `stuff`, `updates`, `work on project` |
| `Refactor stage day time helpers` | vague one-word subjects |

## Scope with other project rules

- When a slice includes the matching **`CHANGELOG.md`** line or **`docs/USER_GUIDE.md`** tweak, commit them **in the same commit** as that slice. Full workflow order: **[`agents-process.mdc`](agents-process.mdc)** / **[`AGENTS.md`](../../AGENTS.md)**.

## If Git is unavailable

If the workspace is **not** a Git repository or commits fail (permissions, etc.), note that for the user instead of skipping silently.
